However, asteroseismology is often equated to just the application of seismic scaling relations (Brown et al. 1991; Kjeldsen & Bedding 1995). These relations, anchored to the Sun, rely on only two seismic observables (
 and 
) to describe the global characteristics of the oscillations, providing estimates of stellar radius and mass, and, with the aid of models, stellar age. Despite their widespread use, the accuracy of these scaling relations, which are partly empirical in nature, remains not fully established (Huber et al. 2011; Miglio et al. 2012; Belkacem et al. 2013; Brogaard et al. 2018; Hekker 2020).

